    <question>
        <prompt>Carlos Montezuma's significance in the 1920s stemmed from his:</prompt>
        <options>
            <option letter="a">Support for assimilation policies</option>
            <option letter="b">Advocacy for Native American rights and self-determination</option>
            <option letter="c">Leadership of the Bureau of Indian Affairs</option>
            <option letter="d">Support for reservation expansion</option>
        </options>
        <answer>b</answer>
        <explanation>Carlos Montezuma, a Yavapai physician and activist, was a prominent advocate for Native American rights and self-determination. He strongly opposed the Bureau of Indian Affairs' paternalistic policies, advocated for Indigenous sovereignty, and fought for improved healthcare and education in Native communities. His work helped lay the groundwork for later Native American rights movements.</explanation>
    </question>
